    "body": "**Description:**\r\n\r\n`scoped_connection`'s move-assignment operator is currently defaulted (`= default`), which overwrites `m_conn` without first disconnecting the previously held connection. This means the old callback remains registered in the signal and continues to fire indefinitely — violating the RAII contract.\r\n\r\n**Reproduction:**\r\n\r\n```cpp\r\nbtcsignals::signal<void(int&)> sig;\r\nint val{0};\r\n\r\nbtcsignals::scoped_connection sc0 = sig.connect(IncrementCallback);\r\nbtcsignals::scoped_connection sc1 = sig.connect(SquareCallback);\r\nsc0 = std::move(sc1);\r\n\r\nval = 3;\r\nsig(val);\r\n// Expected: 9 (only SquareCallback runs)\r\n// Actual:  16 (both IncrementCallback AND SquareCallback run)\r\n```\r\n\r\nAfter move-assignment, `sc0` should own only the new connection, and the old one should be disconnected. Instead, `IncrementCallback` leaks and keeps firing.\r\n\r\n**Fix:**\r\n\r\nReplace the defaulted move-assignment operator with a custom one that calls `disconnect()` before moving. Also handle self-move-assignment safely.\r\n\r\n**Testing:**\r\n\r\nAdded `scoped_connection_move_assignment` test case that verifies:\r\n- Move-assigning disconnects the old connection (old callback stops firing)\r\n- Self-move-assignment is safe (callback continues working)\r\n\r\nTest **fails** on current master (produces `16` instead of `9`) and **passes** with this fix.",
